07579nam a22010095i 9783110740202DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021938136  a97831107402027 a10.1515/97831107402022doi  a(DE-B1597)576761  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aHIS0350002bisacsh00aDigital Roots :bHistoricizing Media and Communication Concepts of the Digital Age /ced. by Valérie Schafer, Gabriele Balbi, Nelson Ribeiro, Christian Schwarzenegger. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VI, 318 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Digital History and Hermeneutics ;v400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tDigging into Digital Roots. Towards a Conceptual Media and Communication History -- tTechnologies and Connections -- tNetworks -- tMedia Convergence -- tMultimedia -- tInteractivity -- tArtificial Intelligence -- tAgency and Politics -- tGlobal Governance -- tData(fication) -- tFake News -- tEcho Chambers -- tDigital Media Activism -- tUsers and Practices -- tTelepresence -- tDigital Loneliness -- tAmateurism -- tUser-Generated Content (UGC) -- tFandom -- tAuthenticity -- tAuthors0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aAs media environments and communication practices evolve over time, so do theoretical concepts. This book analyzes some of the most well-known and fiercely discussed concepts of the digital age from a historical perspective, showing how many of them have pre-digital roots and how they have changed and still are constantly changing in the digital era. Written by leading authors in media and communication studies, the chapters historicize 16 concepts that have become central in the digital media literature, focusing on three main areas. The first part, Technologies and Connections, historicises concepts like network, media convergence, multimedia, interactivity and artificial intelligence. The second one is related to Agency and Politics and explores global governance, datafication, fake news, echo chambers, digital media activism. The last one, Users and Practices, is finally devoted to telepresence, digital loneliness, amateurism, user generated content, fandom and authenticity. The book aims to shed light on how concepts emerge and are co-shaped, circulated, used and reappropriated in different contexts. It argues for the need for a conceptual media and communication history that will reveal new developments without concealing continuities and it demonstrates how the analogue/digital dichotomy is often a misleading one.  afunded by University of Luxembourg  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aDigitale Geschichte. 4aDigitale Kultur. 4aDigitalisierung. 4aMedienkommunikation. 7aHISTORY / Study & Teaching.2bisacsh  aCommunication concepts.  aDigital age.  aHistory.  aMedia studies.1 aAasman, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalbi, Gabriele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalbi, Gabriele, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBenecchi, Eleonora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBolin, Göran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBory, Paolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourdon, Jérôme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrennan, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDa